ce:section.ce:para:
Inspired by the above things, a sulfuric acid-mediated mediated synthetic strategy was developed to prepare N, S-codoped red CDs by separately using N-phenyl-o-phenylenediamine as precursor, sulfuric acid as the acid additive, water as solvent for the first time. The morphology and structural characteristics properties of the as-prepared red CDs (called as R-CDs) were systematacially investigated by using TEM, XPS and FT-IR. Further, the optical properties of R-CDs were measured through UV–vis and fluorescence analysis. Ascribed to the extraordinary performance in fluorescence effects and rich functional group characteristics (e.g. –OH, –NH, -C = O, C-S), R-CDs showed great potential as sensing platform for food dyes including amaranth, brilliant blue FCF and methylene blue (Structures were described in 
                        Figure S1
                     ). To evaluate the effectiveness of R-CDs based sensor platform for the detection of three food dyes, the sensitivity and selectivity were evaluated. Further, to clarify the mechanism of interaction between R-CDs and dyes, UV–vis spectra, fluorescence lifetimes and Stern-Volmer values were measured. Finally, R-CDs based fluorescence sensing platform was applied to the detection of amaranth, brilliant blue FCF in beverages, methylene blue in fish sample. Besides, HPLC assays for amaranth and brilliant blue FCF in beverages, for methylene blue in fish sample were also established. By comparing the results of HPLC method and R-CDs based fluorescence detection method, the real practicability of the constructed platform was further evaluated. Additionally, by virtue of PVA, a R-CDs /PVA composite gel was also made, which avoided the aggregation quenching effect of R-CDs and laid a foundation for the application of R-CDs in visual detection and solid state luminescence. The application potential of R-CDs in cell imaging had also been preliminarily explored, which would lay a foundation for the subsequent application of R-CDs in biological samples.

R-CDs were dissolved in deionized water with the concentration of 25 μg·mL−1. To investigate the sensitivity of R-CDs for three selected food dyes, different concentrations of amaranth, bright blue FCF and methylene blue (volume of them was 300 μL) were added into R-CDs solutions (2.7 mL). The fluorescence intensities of solutions before and after adding different concentrations of three dyes at room temperature were recorded. In addition, other dyes (including malachite green, methyl blue, sunset yellow FCF, eosin Y and lemon yellow, structure were shown in 
                           Figure S1
                        ) and different metal ions (including Zr4+, Er3+, Eu3+, Ba2+, Fe2+, Co2+, Cu2+, Pb2+, K+, Cu+, Bi3+, Mg2+, Cd2+) were selected to investigate the selectivity and anti-interference capability of R-CDs. The F/F0 was employed to measure the abilities of selected dyes or metal ions to quench the fluorescence of R-CDs. F0 and F referred the fluorescence intensities of R-CDs in the presence and absence of selected dyes or metal ions. All fluorescence spectra were acquired at the excitation wavelength of 580 nm.

It is known that the doping of nitrogen (N) and sulfur (S) doping is helpful to redshift the fluorescence emission wavelength of the prepared CDs, and reactive groups like –NH2 can also provide more possibilities for the CDs to emit red fluorescence. Therefore, N-phenyl-o-phenylenediamine with –NH2/–NH groups was employed as precursor and sulfuric acid was used as a dopant of S and a regulator of acid. By using water as solvent, N, S-codoped red R-CDs was successfully synthesized. As shown in Scheme 1, polymerization and carbonization of N-phenyl-o-phenylenediamine and sulfuric acid occurred at 180℃ for 8 h. –NH2 of N-phenyl-o-phenylenediamine and -SO4 of sulfuric acid were successfully introduced into the structure of R-CDs. After neutralizing with NaOH until neutral and dialyzing with a dialysis bag for 7 days, R-CDs with quantum yield (QY) of 5.20% (
                           Figure S2
                        ) was obtained.
